---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
const repo = "https://github.com/ellisgarver/bellwether";
---

<Base title="research" active="research">
  <h1 class="reveal">what bellwether is built on</h1>
  <p class="lede reveal">
    the inspiration, the literature and work which surrounds it, and what it was built for.
  </p>

  <section class="section reveal">
    <h2>a tool for reading the recent past</h2>
    <p>
      bellwether serves as an educational and historical-analysis tool spanning more than fifteen years of
      macro-financial discourse: how stories like the 2013 taper tantrum, the
      transitory-inflation debate, and the 2023 soft-landing turn emerged, took
      hold, peaked, and faded, in the words of the institutions that shaped them,
      alongside how the most recent stories are unfolding both in discourse and press.
    </p>
    <p>
      built to make an exciting yet abstract idea more concrete.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section reveal">
    <h2>the narrative-economics idea</h2>

    <figure class="idea-graphic reveal">
      <svg class="contagion" viewBox="0 0 320 130" aria-hidden="true">
        <line class="edge" x1="60" y1="65" x2="120" y2="30" />
        <line class="edge" x1="60" y1="65" x2="130" y2="100" />
        <line class="edge" x1="120" y1="30" x2="200" y2="42" />
        <line class="edge" x1="130" y1="100" x2="210" y2="92" />
        <line class="edge" x1="200" y1="42" x2="270" y2="65" />
        <line class="edge" x1="210" y1="92" x2="270" y2="65" />
        <circle class="node n-s" cx="60" cy="65" r="9" />
        <circle class="node n-a" cx="120" cy="30" r="8" />
        <circle class="node n-b" cx="130" cy="100" r="8" />
        <circle class="node n-c" cx="200" cy="42" r="8" />
        <circle class="node n-d" cx="210" cy="92" r="8" />
        <circle class="node n-e" cx="270" cy="65" r="9" />
      </svg>
      <figcaption class="sir-key">
        <span><i class="dot s"></i>hasn't heard it</span>
        <span><i class="dot i"></i>carrying it</span>
        <span><i class="dot r"></i>moved on</span>
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      the starting point is Robert Shiller's <em>Narrative Economics</em> (2017 AEA
      presidential address; 2019 book) which details how economic stories spread through a population
      the way contagious ideas do: a story is picked up, carried for a while, and
      eventually dropped. the stories people inevitably carry shape the economic decisions
      they make, so what spreads matters as much as analyzing the fundamentals.
    </p>
    <p>
      bellwether takes the measurable part of that idea, that narratives have
      life-cycles, and reads them directly from the record:
      each stage comes straight from the volume trajectory of institutional macro
      writing, model-free, so no reading depends on any one theory of how stories
      spread being right. the contagion picture above survives as one of three
      interpretive lenses fit alongside (epidemic, growth, and adoption curves),
      each a different account of the same measured shape, shown with how well
      it actually fits that story.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section reveal">
    <h2>field-standard parameters</h2>
    <p>
      every parameter in the pipeline is a published library default or a value
      taken from the primary literature with a citation. all of them live in a
      single configuration file, and every random step flows from one fixed seed ("Don't Panic.").
      where no field-accepted anchor exists, the parameter has been removed, and
      parameters have not been adjusted to make the output look better.
    </p>
    <p class="muted">
      see the full methodology, with citations in
      <a href={`${repo}/blob/main/docs/METHODOLOGY.md`} target="_blank" rel="noopener">METHODOLOGY.md</a>
      from the repository.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section reveal">
    <h2>references &amp; related work</h2>
    <p>
      similarly, the pipeline itself stands on named and field respected research at every step: Shiller's
      narrative-economics program, the text-as-data literature in economics, the
      growth, epidemic, and diffusion models behind the lenses, and the
      embed/cluster and trend-test methods — ranging from Verhulst
      (1838) to the current LLM-frontier papers.
    </p>
    <p class="muted">
      see the full references and the surrounding literature, paper by paper, in
      <a href={`${repo}/blob/main/docs/related_work.md`} target="_blank" rel="noopener">related_work.md</a>
      from the repository.
    </p>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  /* contagion motif: a small SIR spread that loops — one seed infects its
     neighbours, then everyone recovers. */
  .idea-graphic { margin: 1.2rem auto 1.4rem; max-width: 340px; text-align: center; }
  .contagion { width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }
  .edge { stroke: var(--line); stroke-width: 1.4; opacity: 0.5; }
  .node { fill: var(--faint); animation: infect 7.5s ease-in-out infinite; }
  @keyframes infect {
    0%, 8% { fill: var(--faint); }
    20% { fill: var(--ember); }
    42% { fill: var(--ember); }
    60%, 92% { fill: var(--growth); }
    100% { fill: var(--faint); }
  }
  .n-s { animation-delay: 0s; } .n-a { animation-delay: 0.7s; } .n-b { animation-delay: 0.9s; }
  .n-c { animation-delay: 1.5s; } .n-d { animation-delay: 1.7s; } .n-e { animation-delay: 2.4s; }
  .sir-key {
    display: flex; gap: 1.1rem; justify-content: center; flex-wrap: wrap;
    margin-top: 0.5rem; color: var(--muted); font-size: var(--fs-meta);
  }
  .sir-key span { display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.35rem; }
  .sir-key .dot { width: 0.6rem; height: 0.6rem; border-radius: 50%; display: inline-block; }
  .sir-key .s { background: var(--faint); }
  .sir-key .i { background: var(--ember); }
  .sir-key .r { background: var(--growth); }

  @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
    .node { animation: none; fill: var(--growth); }
  }

</style>
